127-Value per Quality-Adjusted Life Year
128-The HHS Guidelines discuss several approaches to valuing morbidity risk reductions. One approach uses
129:quality-adjusted life years (QALYs), a nonmonetary measure that integrates the duration and severity of illness.
130:QALYs are derived by multiplying the amount of time an individual spends in a health state by a measure of the
131-health-related quality of life associated with that state. To quantify benefits using this approach, analysts
132:multiply estimates of the change in QALYs by a monetary value per QALY (VQALY). HHS computes VQALY
133-following a similar procedure as VSLY, except this metric incorporates measurements of age-varying, but
134-otherwise population-average, health-related quality-of-life scores. 13 Based on these scores and the data and
135-other assumptions used to compute remaining life expectancy, we calculate that an individual 40 years of age
136:has an expected 33.6 remaining QALYs. When applying 3% and 7% discount rates, this is a present value of
137:19.5 QALYs and 11.7 QALYs, respectively. Table 2, below, reports the intermediate calculation of future QALYs,
138:and Table 3 reports the range of VQALY estimates, which apply the measure of future QALYs to the full range
139-of VSL estimates. For morbidity risk or other health-related quality-of-life changes occurring in 2026, we adopt
140:$726,000 as the central estimate of VQALY for analyses using a 3% discount rate, and $1,205,000 for analyses
141-using a 7% discount rate.
