151:@tbl-cause decomposes the mean estimate by cause. The result is the paper's central contrast: the global health and development slice — `{python} F["abroad_share_1"]` of dollars — contributes `{python} F["gh_share"]` of estimated QALYs, at a realized cost of about $10,000 per QALY against $350,000–$450,000 for the large U.S. buckets. The 1,200-fold spread in realized cost-effectiveness within a single donor's portfolio is partly the lens speaking — its low end is dominated by assumption-tier buckets whose near-zero credibility is an input, and whose main benefits QALYs do not count — but the spread among evidenced health buckets alone exceeds an order of magnitude, restating in one column an empirical regularity long emphasized in the effective-altruism literature [@ord2013]: the cheapest health in the world is not bought where most philanthropic dollars are spent.
